In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to assert the type of a value, indicating to the type system that you know the value will have a specific type even though its type might be inferred as a broader type.

Here's an example:
```typescript
// Given
const value = 10;

// Using 'as' to assert the type
const valueAsNumber = value as number;

// Now, TypeScript knows that 'valueAsNumber' has type 'number'
console.log(valueAsNumber); // Output: 10
```
In this example, the `value` variable is inferred to have a type of `any`, which is the most general type. By using the `as` keyword, you're telling TypeScript that you know the value is a number, so it should be treated as a `number`.

You can also use the `as` keyword with interfaces, classes, and other types to assert the type of a value.

Keep in mind that asserting a type doesn't change the type of the original value; it only tells TypeScript to treat the value as a specific type for the purposes of type checking and type inference.

If you're working with third-party libraries or code that you don't have control over, you might not be able to assert the types, as you might not have enough information to do so. In those cases, you can use type guards or the `infer` keyword to help TypeScript understand the types involved.

